 H. Rider Haggard, Bram Stoker, Rudyard Kipling, and Joseph Conrad. Demonstrating the investment of modernist writing in the problems of geopolitics and in the public discourse of time, Barrows argues that it is possible, and productive, to rethink the politics of modernism through the politics of time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zEnglish-speaking countries. 0aTime in literature. 0aTimexPolitical aspects. 0aTimexSystems and standards. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  a1884.  aadventure novels.  abackward arrow.  abram stoker.  acosmopolitan clock.  aempire.  ageopolitics.  aglobe.  agreenwich.  ah rider haggard.  ahigh modernism.  ahuman temporality.  aimperialism.  aindia.  aindian literature.  ajames joyce.  ajoseph conrad.  aliterary criticism.  amodern literature.  amodernism.  amodernist.  amodernity.  anature of time.  anegri.  apolitics.  aprime meridian.  arudyard kipling.  ascience.  asemiotics theory.  asouth asian novels.  astandard time.  atemporality.  atime.  avictorian culture.  avictorian literature.  avirginia woolf.  aworld standard time.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026099340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094815040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520948150/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY